*Conclusion (English)*

This master's thesis presents the development of a configuration management system for heterogeneous computing infrastructure based on the declarative operating system NixOS.

The research analyzed existing approaches to configuration management, compared state management models (divergent, convergent, congruent), and identified limitations of traditional tools (Ansible, Puppet, Chef).

A mathematical model for evaluating configuration management quality was developed, introducing an integral quality index $Q_(C M)$ that accounts for module reusability, system modularity, code reduction, and redundancy.

A three-tier modular architecture was designed and implemented: modules (25) → suites (5) → profiles (13) with an inheritance mechanism. The vladOS-v2 system was developed to manage 3 hosts of different purposes.

Experimental evaluation demonstrated the following quality metric values: modularity 0.52, code reduction 62%, redundancy 7%, quality index 0.44. The time to add a new host was reduced from 60–120 minutes to 10–15 minutes.

*Keywords:* configuration management, NixOS, Infrastructure as Code, declarative approach, modular architecture, Nix Flakes, Snowfall Lib, DevOps.
